879151008" about="#mwt21" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ISBN","href":"./Template:ISBN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"978-0-231-10335-0"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAhs"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" about="#mwt21" id="mwAhw">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt21" id="mwAh0"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-231-10335-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-231-10335-0" about="#mwt21" id="mwAh4">978-0-231-10335-0</a>, p. 2, Quote: "The main current of Hinduism – if not the only one – which became formalized in a way that approximates to an ecclesiastical structure was that of Shankara".</span></li><li about="#cite_note-SriAdi-10" id="cite_note-SriAdi-10"><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-SriAdi_10-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-SriAdi-10" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.sringeri.net/history/sri-adi-shankaracharya" id="mwAh8">Sri Adi Shankaracharya</a>, Sringeri Sharada Peetham, India</span></li><li about="#cite_note-11" id="cite_note-11"><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-11" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-11" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt28" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://scroll.in/article/816610/how-adi-shankaracharya-united-a-fragmented-land-with-philosophy-poetry-and-pilgrimage"},"title":{"wt":"How Adi Shankaracharya united a fragmented land with philosophy, poetry and pilgrimage"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAiA"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://scroll.in/article/816610/how-adi-shankaracharya-united-a-fragmented-land-with-philosophy-poetry-and-pilgrimage" id="mwAiE">"How Adi Shankaracharya united a fragmented land with philosophy, poetry and pilgrimage"</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=How+Adi+Shankaracharya+united+a+fragmented+land+with+philosophy%2C+poetry+and+pilgrimage&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fscroll.in%2Farticle%2F816610%2Fhow-adi-shankaracharya-united-a-fragmented-land-with-philosophy-poetry-and-pilgrimage&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAdi+Shankara" class="Z3988" about="#mwt28" id="mwAiI"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt28" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAiM"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-SKChattopadhyaya-12" id="cite_note-SKChattopadhyaya-12"><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-SKChattopadhyaya_12-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-SKChattopadhyaya-12" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?ei=09d0T6ygK4PTrQf5l4SgDQ&amp;id=IPasbJW-1PwC&amp;dq=inauthor%3A%22Shyama+Kumar+Chattopadhyaya%22&amp;q=Mimamsa#v=snippet&amp;q=Mimamsa&amp;f=false" id="mwAiQ">Shyama Kumar Chattopadhyaya (2000) <i id="mwAiU">The Philosophy of Sankar's Advaita Vedanta</i></a>, Sarup &amp; Sons, New Delhi <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt29" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ISBN","href":"./Template:ISBN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"81-7625-222-0"},"2":{"wt":"978-81-7625-222-5"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAiY"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" about="#mwt29" id="mwAic">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt29" id="mwAig"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/81-7625-222-0" title="Special:BookSources/81-7625-222-0" about="#mwt29" id="mwAik">81-7625-222-0</a><span about="#mwt29" id="mwAio">, </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-81-7625-222-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-7625-222-5" about="#mwt29" id="mwAis">978-81-7625-222-5</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-eroer1-13" id="cite_note-eroer1-13"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-eroer1_13-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-eroer1_13-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-eroer1_13-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-eroer1-13" class="mw-reference-text">Edward Roer (Translator),  to <i id="mwAiw">Brihad Aranyaka Upanishad</i>. <i about="#mwt366" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Google books","href":"./Template:Google_books"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"3uwDAAAAMAAJ"},"2":{"wt":"Shankara&apos;s Introduction"},"pages":{"wt":"3–4"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAi0"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=3uwDAAAAMAAJ" id="mwAi4">Shankara's Introduction</a></i><span about="#mwt366" id="mwAi8"> at </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Google_Books" title="Google Books" about="#mwt366" id="mwAjA">Google Books</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-eroer2-14" id="cite_note-eroer2-14"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-eroer2_14-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Adi_Shankara#cite_ref-eroer2_14-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-eroer2-14" class="mw-reference-text">Edward Roer (Translator), <i about="#mwt30" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Google books","href":"./Template:Google_books"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"3uw